SECTION 6 — Falsification
Phase Misclassification Conditions
Premature Transition: new form appears before prior constraint reaches zero valid states and fails Bounded Recurrence Check (destabilizes within <3 cycles).
Oscillation: Resolution Check fails indefinitely.
Collapse: no new form after mismatch.
Fragmentation: linkages form but never activate coherently.
Geometric Instability Modes (practical tests)
Apply one perturbation at a time; system must remain in toroidal, membrane-mediated topology. Failure = reversion or collapse.
External Constraint Flood
Sudden large increase in unresolved external constraints.
Expected: temporary oscillation → re-stabilization in current basin.
Failure: immediate reversion to hierarchical or non-membrane-mediated interaction (direct O↔S coupling appears).
Resonance Decoupling
Temporarily isolate one sovereign (O, S, or R) from membrane interaction.
Expected: instability spike → rapid re-coupling.
Failure: permanent domain collapse or emergence of direct O↔S channel.
Boundary Erosion
Gradually weaken R-membrane permeability controls.
Expected: controlled leakage → re-tightening via next constraint.
Failure: domains bleed into one another (loss of O ≠ R ≠ S).
Premature Acceleration
Force phase advance by artificially satisfying next constraint before current resolution.
Expected: N/A (model forbids).
Failure: immediate destabilization of apparent new form + reversion to prior basin.
Reversion to hierarchical or non-membrane-mediated interaction
Any of the above producing:
hierarchy (one domain dominates)
direct O↔S coupling
loss of membrane mediation
reversal of phase direction
= total falsification of CTA-XXV geometry.

